Keep a variable that can be accessed by both the background worker and UI code. To be simple lets keep it as a public static variable.

    public class YourClass
    {
       public static bool IsBackgroundProcessActive = true;
    }

Now when you work with the message box change that variable.

    if(MessageBox.Show(&quot;convert is okey&quot;)
    {
        yourClass.IsBackgroundProcessActive  = false;
    }

Now you need to make the background worker listen to this variable.
For most common cases this background worker will be a loop with a simple process. So you can set the loop condition to check this variable,

    private void YourBackgroundWorkerFunction()
    {
        while(yourClass.IsBackgroundProcessActive)
        {
           // Your simple iterative task 
        }
    }

For complex cases where the background worker is not a simple loop, you can use an exception to stop the thread. For that case write a simple function as,

    private void MarkAsSafeToStop()
    {
        if(!yourClass.IsBackgroundProcessActive)
        {
            throw new OperationCancelledException();
        }
    }

Then use this function in several places of your background worker function. Then the background worker will stop with an exception whenever you reach this function after clicking the message box.

ie

    private void YourBackgroundWorkerFunction()
    {
       // Some code
       MarkAsSafeToStop();
       // Some other code
       MarkAsSafeToStop();
       // and so on.
    }

